Partition the square into four congruent squares of side length $1/2.$ Then at least one of these squares must contain two of the five points, say $A$ and $B.$ Then the distance between $A$ and $B$ is at most $\sqrt{(1/2)^2 + (1/2)^2} = \sqrt{1/2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

filldraw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,1)--(0,1)--cycle,gray(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,1)--(0,1)--cycle);
draw((0,0.5)--(1,0.5));
draw((0.5,0)--(0.5,1));
[/asy]

Now, we show that it is possible to have five points such that the distance between any two points is greater than $\sqrt{1/2}.$  Place a point at the center of the square, and place the other four points at the midpoints of the sides of the square.  Then the distance between any two points is $\sqrt{2}/2,$ which is greater than $\sqrt{1/2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

filldraw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,1)--(0,1)--cycle,gray(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,1)--(0,1)--cycle);
dot((0.5,0.5));
dot((0,0.5));
dot((1,0.5));
dot((0.5,0));
dot((0.5,1));
[/asy]

Therefore, the smallest such $a$ is $\boxed{\sqrt{1/2}}.$

